07:55.203 --> 07:57.486
would be 59. I went to school in 57. 57, came back in 
59, and I think I became assistant director. I'm

08:04.476 --> 08:06.419
coming into the rudder years now, I guess. That's 
the same year I got here. I came back here in 59, in

08:07.881 --> 08:15.231
the spring of 59, and was involved in several 
special projects.

08:18.451 --> 08:27.303
Describe, as you came as assistant director, 
describe the Extension Service and its

08:18.451 --> 08:27.303
leadership. What was its organization? Well, 
John Hutchison was director by then, and he was an

08:30.327 --> 08:35.654
outstanding director. And I enjoyed serving with 
him. He was director, I guess, 19 years. And J.D.

08:45.286 --> 08:47.209
Pruitt was associate director. They made a good 
combination, Mr. Pruitt was not a what you call a

08:48.033 --> 09:08.573
gregarious person to deal with and I had of course 
going through administrative training programs

08:48.033 --> 09:08.573
I had always felt that an organization would work 
effectively if you could have what I call the Mr.

09:08.806 --> 09:10.448
Outside and Mr. Inside. And the outside man had to 
be the head man because most of the time people

09:10.968 --> 09:16.254
don't want to deal with the number two or three 
person. And I saw that operate. Hutchison was very

09:21.299 --> 09:25.464
effective working with the legislature, with the 
leadership in the state. Mr. Pruitt did the work

09:26.045 --> 09:35.775
back home in terms of all the staffing and budgets 
and personnel problems and all of that. I guess the

09:36.397 --> 09:39.883
administrative staff at that time was about eight 
or nine people. You had a state program leader for

09:39.923 --> 09:49.458
agriculture, one in home economics, 4-H, 
communications, fiscal, personnel, all of those

09:39.923 --> 09:49.458
types of things. And it was a good learning 
experience to work that closely to

09:50.540 --> 09:55.208
administration. Had the black and white agents 
yet been integrated? That came, I guess, In the

10:03.076 --> 10:03.877
60s. That involved me very heavily. Oh, okay. We 
had to go through a lot of the things at that time

10:08.544 --> 10:14.033
with that program. And also I got a lot of special 
assignments. Kellogg at that time had financed

10:19.882 --> 10:31.480
another program called the National Agriculture 
Communications Project, centered at Iowa State

10:19.882 --> 10:31.480
University, in which they trained two or three 
people in each state intensively, and it was kind

10:32.000 --> 10:45.394
of the in-thing then of principles of 
communication, organizations function better,

10:32.000 --> 10:45.394
people could communicate better, and you could 
reach audiences better. There was a lot of this was

10:45.934 --> 11:00.910
based on Bowen and Beale's sociology work at Iowa 
State where they learned how the process of how new

10:45.934 --> 11:00.910
ideas are accepted, they call it the fusion 
process, of when people first hear about a new

10:45.934 --> 11:00.910
idea. how they go about the mental processes they 
go through, and finally accepting a new variety of

11:01.396 --> 11:10.006
corn or a new way of doing things or something. We 
were given training.

11:20.039 --> 11:27.808
Three of us were selected to participate in an 
intensive three-week program at the University

11:20.039 --> 11:27.808
of Wyoming. And then we came back, and we had to 
train everybody in the staff, all 1,100, 1,200

11:28.447 --> 11:51.990
people that were on the staff about that time in 
district meetings, different kinds of state

11:28.447 --> 11:51.990
meetings, two or three day, I guess, meetings 
where we gave everybody this

11:28.447 --> 11:51.990
type of training. interpersonal relations and 
communications and how you get ideas across to

11:53.253 --> 11:59.519
people and get them to accept them and all this type 
of thing. That was a very exciting project. As I

12:02.522 --> 12:04.704
said, I was involved in special things. Back in the 
county, I had already gotten extremely

12:05.405 --> 12:20.560
frustrated with the lack of any guidance in terms 
of how files were kept in the counties because the

12:05.405 --> 12:20.560
county agents had to depository of all kinds of 
information. And you had a real problem. Every

12:23.387 --> 12:27.151
county agent set up their own system, and no two 
people think. And I guess part of that was my

12:28.052 --> 12:30.215
library experience. I knew that you could 
organize things. And so I started out in the county

12:33.058 --> 12:35.160
of trying. At that time, I had worked in the library 
here. I had to do a decimal system. I thought, well,

12:39.926 --> 12:44.351
why can't you use the same principles, maybe in 
organizing office files? But I found out that that

12:44.431 --> 12:48.876
was a little too complicated for the average 
agent. So I started on my own in the county of

12:49.278 --> 12:53.362
developing a sort of a filing system. And my 
contention was that if there was a similar filing

12:54.403 --> 13:19.048
system in every county, that when agents went from 
one county to the other, they would either face one

12:54.403 --> 13:19.048
problem of learning the other guy's or his 
predecessor's system, which probably was

12:54.403 --> 13:19.048
incomprehensible, or set up his own, which was a 
very huge process because in most counties you had

13:20.041 --> 13:24.988
five or six, ten file cabinets full of 
information. I mean, you had to have, you know,

13:25.048 --> 13:30.015
somebody come in, what's the formula for a 
whitewashing offense? I mean, you don't remember

13:30.135 --> 13:34.181
these things, you have to have a place to find this 
information. And so I, so it had been tried before

13:35.183 --> 13:41.412
three or three times in Texas and always bogged 
down. It had been tried in other states, it had been

13:41.492 --> 13:46.339
tried nationally, and I said, I think I can do it. 
And I was given full time off and resources to do it,

13:49.471 --> 13:58.200
and I developed this system in about a year's time, 
but I involved everybody in the staff, every

13:49.471 --> 13:58.200
specialist. We set up the sections by 
disciplines, animal science, but we did it as an

13:59.081 --> 14:05.627
agent would look at it. You know, he wouldn't look 
at it in terms of, you know, breeding and so forth,

14:05.848 --> 14:12.755
but he would look at it from the way he does it. So we 
set up a rather elaborate filing system, and we

14:13.275 --> 14:18.060
went We trained, gave people, everybody in the 
state, a full day training program on it, and even

14:18.344 --> 14:28.454
provided the materials of the dividers, the 
guidance, and so forth. So that was a very, I

14:28.914 --> 14:35.221
thought it was a thing that made a great 
contribution to the organization. And as far as I

14:35.341 --> 14:38.644
know, the system is still being utilized. So I was 
kind of jumping from projects to projects. And

14:44.650 --> 14:46.832
gradually, I was beginning. what I'd call more 
real administrative responsibilities.

14:53.041 --> 14:56.485
When you started out, did you replace anybody? No, 
no, I think it was more of a new slot for special

14:56.846 --> 15:02.914
projects, I guess you'd call it. But gradually I 
was given responsibility over units of other

15:03.975 --> 15:14.389
people, like in that period of time, community 
development became a big new thrust from the

15:14.555 --> 15:37.997
Lyndon Johnson, you know, working with 
low-income farmers and so forth, and I started

15:14.555 --> 15:37.997
giving leadership to some of those kind of 
programs, or had the people that were employed in

15:14.555 --> 15:37.997
those areas, and got involved in, I was always 
available for special things, the Century Study,

15:14.555 --> 15:37.997
I got stuck in that. That was in the 60s. Mr. Rutter 
was, early on, was president of both the campus and

