At about that time, I would guess in engineering 
and agriculture that 80% of the faculty were A&M

18:20.770 --> 18:29.941
graduates themselves. Of course, then the 
decision was made to try to get more outside, which

18:30.341 --> 18:36.989
was necessary if the school was going to grow. But I 
think there was a lot of resentment on the pure

18:37.890 --> 18:46.120
academics that he had no academic credentials as 
such. Now, as far as I remember, the Century Study

18:46.758 --> 18:55.926
is 62-3-4, and you were appointed to the 
committee, weren't you? They had four task

18:56.186 --> 18:59.869
forces. I worked with one of the task forces. 
That's what I thought. The chairman I worked with

19:03.993 --> 19:09.697
was Harry Moore, and they had 25. Describe what you 
can remember of that task force's work. Describe

19:14.221 --> 19:16.343
what that task force did. Well, it was a very 
interesting experience. I mean, these were the

19:18.653 --> 19:27.987
very top people in Texas, political, industrial, 
business, agricultural, you name it, top

19:18.653 --> 19:27.987
leaders, men and women. all parts of the state. It 
was interesting to see how they interacted and

19:30.446 --> 19:35.174
became a group and made their recommendation. I 
think each task force has sort of an area to look at.

19:38.860 --> 19:43.027
And the staff person was kind of the go-for. You 
know, made arrangements for the meetings and got

19:43.648 --> 19:49.738
the resource people they needed, kept notes of the 
meeting and wrote up their materials, which were

19:50.005 --> 19:55.632
turned into your group, I guess, and processed 
them somehow. I don't remember all the details,

19:56.333 --> 19:59.277
but it was an interesting experience. Do you think 
that was an important activity in terms of its

19:59.297 --> 20:03.943
long-range results? It was absolutely 
essential. A&M would not have been anywhere from

20:05.305 --> 20:19.624
my viewpoint where they are today, because the 
report dealt with the basic issues about

20:05.305 --> 20:19.624
co-education, mandatory core thing, name 
change, all of those things, as I think we

20:20.414 --> 20:25.639
indicated before. My own conclusion is nobody 
could have done this other than Earl Rudder,

20:26.880 --> 20:36.010
because he did have a non-academic background, 
but he knew that he had to have the state

20:26.880 --> 20:36.010
leadership. If the state leadership made these 
recommendations, that they would be more

20:37.051 --> 20:42.996
acceptable, and I think it turned out that way. Do 
you remember any opinions Dr. Hutchinson had

20:43.297 --> 20:48.582
about some of those basic changes?

20:51.380 --> 20:55.484
Well, he didn't, I mean, he didn't, deliberately 
didn't try to influence me. I was just pretty much,

20:55.544 --> 20:58.887
I guess that was almost a full-time assignment 
those days. Almost. I mean, I didn't. Like, I never

21:01.249 --> 21:04.151
heard of his being for or against. No, I think he was 
a true blue Aggie, and I think he had to, but he was

21:04.191 --> 21:11.537
also progressive. He'd gone to the University of 
Chicago and got his Ph.D. I mean, I think he

21:14.880 --> 21:20.205
recognized that some of the change, but he tended 
to be, you know, conservative, uh, I know he had a

